      {
        "id": 4522746,
        "name": "Todd Tucker",
        "username": "Todd_Tucker",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/todd_tucker/{size}/76924_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-12-07T04:50:46.584Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Everyone is back in town, and we decided for a Saturday afternoon \u201cbring something above average and interesting\u201d tasting. All wines were served blind. Overall a very fun afternoon.</p>\n<p>To start:</p>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=2029438\"><b>2013 Hubert Lamy Chassagne-Montrachet Le Concis du Champs</b></a> - France, Burgundy, C\u00f4te de Beaune, Chassagne-Montrachet (11/23/2024)<br>\nTasted blind<br><br>A fantastic nose. Chalky and flinty, with a mix of orchard and citrus fruit. Mid weighted and toothsome with terrific cut. Intensity without heaviness. Great textural depth, terrific extract, and fantastic balance. This has a jewel like focus to it with weightless power. This is so much better than one would expect. While this has time in hand, I feel like we caught this wine at its absolute apogee. Hold if you want, but why, it's about as good as I can imagine it being. I love Hubert Lamy. <b>(94 points)</b></li>\n\n<p>Posted from <a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com\">CellarTracker</a></p>\n<p>this wine was so much better than on would expect, although I have learned not to underestimate Hubert Lamy. A terrific bootle of wine and another reason why this is my favorite producer of white  Burgundy.</p>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=2458869\"><b>2015 Edmond Vatan Sancerre Clos la N\u00e9ore</b></a> - France, Loire Valley, Upper Loire, Sancerre (11/23/2024)<br>\nPop and pour, drunk over a couple hours with friends. Served blind<br><br>A fantastic nose. Citrus and pear fruit with some hints at tropical, stones, florals and stone. It feels like maybe a touch of botrytis. Mid plus weighted, implausibly deep and expansive on the palate with a sense of stoniness and clarity that is frankly terrific. There's flesh and ripeness and just a little grassiness, but no other SB herbal greenness, as acyso described as mercifully missing. Toothsome and dense yet simultaneously deft and agile. This dances on the palate. A 6'5\" 250 pound tight end who is also a ballerina. At peak with time in hand, but another wine to ask \"why wait\". Fantastic. Singular. 95 <b>(95 points)</b></li>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=448\"><b>1989 Ch\u00e2teau Margaux</b></a> - France, Bordeaux, M\u00e9doc, Margaux (11/23/2024)<br>\nDouble decanted in the AM. Drunk over a couple hours with friends and a last glass saved for the next day<br><br>Served blind<br><br>A beguiling nose. Cassis and stone fruits, bitter chocolate, bricks, violets and wet tobacco.Interestingly, the florals on the nose weren't really in the fore, but after an hour or two open, no pun intended, it really blossomed. It's full bodied, sapid and expansive on the palate. This just flows over the palate with effortless intensity. Power and grace coupled.Texturally brilliant. Seamless. Regal. While I love an overperforming underdog, this wine is a reason why there is a classification system. There is just an extra dimension here. Tremendous depth and complexity with a sense of calm. At what I suspect is early peak with decades in hand. Fantastic. 97<br><br>I guessed 89 or 90 Pauillac First or a super second. K for close. <br><br>Day two this is still going strong. Brilliant <b>(97 points)</b></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/wine.asp?iWine=7033\"><b>1998 Ch\u00e2teau de Beaucastel Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape Hommage \u00e0 Jacques Perrin</b></a> - France, Rh\u00f4ne, Southern Rh\u00f4ne, Ch\u00e2teauneuf-du-Pape (11/23/2024)<br>\nFrom the same OWC of my last bottle drunk in 2008. Double decanted for sediment in the AM, quite tight at the time, then followed for a few hors, still tight, so decanted for a couple hours. Drunk over a few hours with friends. <br><br>Served blind<br><br>A complex and rich nose with dark berry fruits, olives, roasted meat, porcini, ink, garrigue, lavender, and thyme: an excellent mix of fruit and savory. Full bodied, powerful and rich on the palate. Stony and deep with more of the same black fruits, and savory meaty herbal notes. There is a little of the fruit leaning toward prune on the palate. This is very deep, overtly powerful, and hugely structured. It's funny, I bet this is is quite similar to the bottle I tasted in '08, excepting the years between. The difference is me. This just doesn't turn my crank anymore. This is brilliantly made wine achieving its goal in spades. Impressive and admirable? Absolutely. Did I love it? No. If this is your jam, it is fantastic and drinking at peak with time in hand.<br><br>FWIW, the three people blinded were guessing late 90s early 00s very high quality CdP producer. <b>(94 points)</b></li>\n<p>Overall it was a great afternoon to reconnect with close friends. Some special wines and an educational tasting to boot. The Lamy was so good, the Vatan singularly fantastic, and the Margaux Regal. The Hommage was impressive but no longer what I want to drink. Life is learning and progression and this was a great insight into that journey. Some day, this trend may alter its course or even reverse. Mostly, this was about spending several hours with great friends and appreciating our good fortune</p>\n<p>Thanks for reading.</p></ul>",
